> Back in memory lane...
>
> I built a diode detector around a bit more than 40 years ago and used it =
as
> "HiFi" AM tuner, and it sounded pretty well with local AM stations.
>
> Used just a common 100 turn coil with many taps, no ferrite, and was dead=
 as
> a rock without a longish piece of wire as antenna. Never put earphones on
> it, but gave a fairly acceptable line level output of a Fisher audio
> amplifier, with a Williamson's Ultra Linear amplifier with a pair of KT66=
's
> and a large baffle. So even without ferrite losses, it needed a wire ante=
nna
> to work as I expected. THAT did make quite a bit of noise...
>
> The idea came from a late 50's booklet with practical circuits for a TRF
> tuner, only that I did not go into the trouble of building the two 6SK7
> amplification stages and went direct to the detector... There were, and
> still are, several 10 to 50 kW national networks transmitters around Hava=
na
> in a 10 to 20 km radius, so getting strong signals on medium wave was not=
 a
> problem.
>
> Jose, CO2JA
